 Italy, and Canada, which were only just coming into their own as states. In war, Martin observes, these documents also represented a non-verbal method of communicating emotionally trying, politically challenging, and oftentimes contradictory information to the public, literate and non-literate alike.The history of nineteenth-century illustrated papers underscores their legitimacy as a form of journalism. They were more than a commodity produced for profit; they offered serious reflection and commentary on the times designed by editors to have specific effects on the readers. Images at War is a much-needed study of this early news medium and its part in the construction of nationalism in the midst of war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFranco-Prussian War, 1870-1871xPress coveragexCanada. 0aFranco-Prussian War, 1870-1871xPress coveragexEurope. 0aFranco-Prussian War, 1870-1871xPress coveragezCanada. 0aFranco-Prussian War, 1870-1871xPress coveragezEurope. 0aGuerre franco-allemande, 1870-1871, dans la pressexCanada. 0aGuerre franco-allemande, 1870-1871, dans la pressexEurope. 0aIllustrated periodicalsxHistoryx19th centuryxCanada. 0aIllustrated periodicalsxHistoryx19th centuryxEurope. 0aIllustrated periodicalszCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aIllustrated periodicalszEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aMagazines (Publications)xHistoirex19e sièclexCanada. 0aMagazines (Publications)xHistoirex19e sièclexEurope. 0aPress and politicsxHistoryx19th centuryxCanada. 0aPress and politicsxHistoryx19th centuryxEurope. 0aPress and politicszCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPress and politicszEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aPresse et politiquexHistoirex19e sièclexCanadaxFrankrijkxDuitslandxEngelandxCanadaxCanadaxEurope. 0aPresse et politiquexHistoirex19e sièclexEu